'''Richmond Mamah Laryea''' ({{IPAc-en|l|æ|'|r|ei|j|æ|}} {{respell|La|RAY|a}};<ref name="pronunciation">{{cite tweet |user=TorontoFC |number=1421897416085839873 |date=August 1, 2021|title=PSA from @RichieLaryea_|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> [[Ga language|Ga]]: {{IPAc-en|'|l|ɑː|j|i|}} {{respell|LAH|yee}};<ref name=pronunciation /> born January 7, 1995) is a Canadian professional [[association football|soccer]] player who plays as a [[right-back]] or [[midfielder]] for [[Major League Soccer]] club [[Toronto FC]] and the [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada national team]].

==College career==
Prior to his college career, Laryea played for [[Sigma FC]] Academy and [[Dante Alighieri Academy]] in Toronto.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sigma FC's Richmond Laryea Signs Generation Adidas Contract with MLS|url=http://www.sigma-sports.net/newsEvents/SigmaFCsRichmondLaryeaSignsGenerationAdidasContractWithMLS.html|publisher=[[Sigma FC]]|archive-date=January 13, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160113201611/http://www.sigma-sports.net/newsEvents/SigmaFCsRichmondLaryeaSignsGenerationAdidasContractWithMLS.html|url-status=dead|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> Laryea played [[College soccer in the United States|college soccer]] at the [[University of Akron]] for two seasons, reaching the [[NCAA Division I Men's Soccer Championship|College Cup]] semi-finals in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cleveland.com/sports/college/index.ssf/2015/12/akron_zips_will_take_on_stanfo.html |title=Akron Zips will take on Stanford on Friday in College Cup 2015 (photos) |website=[[The Plain Dealer]] |date=December 6, 2015 |access-date=January 15, 2016|first=Elton|last=Alexander}}</ref>

Laryea was named to the All-[[Mid-American Conference]] Second Team in 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gozips.com/news/2014/11/13/11_13_2014_5535.aspx?path=msoc|title=Men's Soccer garners a conference-best seven All-MAC selections|website=[[Akron Zips]]|date=November 13, 2014|access-date=May 16, 2020|archive-date=August 30, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220830132343/https://gozips.com/news/2014/11/13/11_13_2014_5535.aspx?path=msoc|url-status=dead}}</ref> and was named to the All-Mid-American Conference First Team in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gozips.com/news/2015/11/12/11_12_2015_5432.aspx?path=msoc|title=Zips Garner a League-Best Eight All-MAC Selections|website=[[Akron Zips]]|date=November 12, 2015|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> Following his sophomore season, Laryea signed a contract with [[Generation Adidas]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2016/01/07/mls-announces-2016-generation-adidas-class |title=MLS announces 2016 Generation adidas class, signs Stanford senior defender Brandon Vincent |website=[[Major League Soccer]]|date=January 9, 2016 |access-date=January 15, 2016}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Sigma FC===
Laryea played for [[League1 Ontario]] club [[Sigma FC]] in 2015, where he was named a League All-Star.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.league1ontario.com/news_article/show/598777|title=2015 League1 Ontario Men's All-Stars|date=November 17, 2015|work=[[League1 Ontario]]|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref>

=== Orlando City ===
Laryea was drafted in the first round (seventh overall) of the [[2016 MLS SuperDraft]] by Orlando City.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/sports/orlando-city-lions/on-the-pitch/os-orlando-city-akron-richie-laryea-no-7-mls-superdraft-20160114-post.html |title=Orlando City selects Akron's Richie Laryea with No. 7 pick in MLS SuperDraft |website=orlandosentinel.com |publisher=[[Orlando Sentinel]]|first=Paul|last=Tenorio|date=January 14, 2016|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.toronto.com/community-story/6240863-dante-alighieri-academy-grad-richie-laryea-taken-seventh-in-mls-draft/|title=Dante Alighieri Academy grad Richie Laryea taken seventh in MLS draft|date=January 20, 2016|work=North York Mirror|first=Norm|last=Nelson|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> He was loaned to [[Orlando City B]] in March 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.orlandocitysc.com/post/2016/03/25/orlando-city-sc-loan-seven-players-ocb|title=Orlando City SC Loan Seven Players to OCB |website=[[Orlando City SC]]|date=March 25, 2016|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref>

After spending the first half of his second season once again on loan to OCB playing as both an attacking and defensive midfielder,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.themaneland.com/2017/5/16/15645066/richie-laryea-starting-to-prove-himself-in-year-2-for-orlando-city-b|title=Richie Laryea Starting To Prove Himself in Year 2 for Orlando City B|first=Austin|last=David|website=The Mane Land|date=May 16, 2017|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> Laryea made his MLS debut on June 25, 2017, subbing on for [[Kaká]] in a 4–0 defeat to [[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/sports/orlando-city-lions/on-the-pitch/os-sp-orlando-city-soccer-insider-0720-story.html|title=Richie Laryea excels with Orlando City after stern talk with coach|first=Alicia|last=del Gallo|publisher=[[Orlando Sentinel]]|date=July 19, 2017|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> Laryea got his first MLS assist on September 27, 2017, assisting on [[Yoshimar Yotún]]'s goal against [[New England Revolution]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.orlandocitysc.com/post/2017/09/28/game-firsts-orlandos-dominant-win-provides-accolades|title=A Game of Firsts: Orlando's Dominant Win Provides Accolades|publisher=[[Orlando City SC]]|date=September 28, 2017|first=Austin|last=David|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> He made his first career MLS start on the final day of the season away to [[Philadelphia Union]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.orlandocitysc.com/post/2017/10/22/orlando-city-falls-philadelphia-season-finale|title=Orlando City Falls at Philadelphia in Season Finale|publisher=[[Orlando City SC]]|date=October 22, 2017|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref>

On November 27, 2018, the club announced they had declined his contract option.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prosoccerusa.com/mls/orlando-city-sc/orlando-city-2018-contract-options/|title=Orlando City declines options for eight players after tough 2018 season |publisher=Pro Soccer USA|language=en-US|date=November 27, 2018|archive-date=November 28, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181128075148/https://www.prosoccerusa.com/mls/orlando-city-sc/orlando-city-2018-contract-options/|url-status=dead|first=Jordan|last=Culver}}</ref>

===Toronto FC===
On March 21, 2019, Laryea signed for MLS side [[Toronto FC]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.torontofc.ca/news/toronto-fc-signs-richie-laryea|title=Toronto FC signs Richie Laryea|work=[[Toronto FC]]|date=March 21, 2019|access-date=March 21, 2019}}</ref> Laryea scored his first goal for Toronto on May 26, 2019, in a 2–1 home defeat to the [[San Jose Earthquakes]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/soccer/toronto-fc-trending-wrong-direction-loss-san-jose/|title=Toronto FC trending in wrong direction with loss to San Jose|work=[[Sportsnet]]|first=John|last=Molinaro|date=May 26, 2019|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> was also his first MLS goal.<ref>{{cite web|title=Recap: Laryea bags his first as TFC fall at home|date=May 26, 2019|first=Charlie|last=O'Connor-Clarke|work=Waking the Red|url=https://www.wakingthered.com/2019/5/26/18640952/toronto-fc-san-jose-earthquakes-mls-game-recap-richie-laryea-highlights|access-date=March 5, 2022|archive-date=August 13, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220813145339/https://www.wakingthered.com/2019/5/26/18640952/toronto-fc-san-jose-earthquakes-mls-game-recap-richie-laryea-highlights|url-status=dead}}</ref> Laryea scored his first playoff goal, against [[DC United]], and then defeated [[Atlanta United FC]] to win the [[Eastern Conference (MLS)]] playoffs. Laryea and [[Toronto FC]] then lost to [[Seattle Sounders FC]] in the [[2019 MLS Cup]] final. Laryea would have his option for the 2020 season exercised by Toronto, keeping him with the club for 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.torontofc.ca/post/2019/11/21/toronto-fc-announces-roster-decisions-conclude-2019-season|title=Toronto FC announces roster decisions to conclude 2019 season|publisher=[[Toronto FC]]|date=November 21, 2019|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref>

On September 27, 2020, Laryea scored a solo goal and provided two assists in the second half of Toronto's 3–1 win against the league-leading [[Columbus Crew]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cp24.com/sports/laryea-puts-on-a-show-as-toronto-fc-rallies-to-down-league-leading-columbus-3-1-1.5122622|title=Laryea puts on a show as Toronto FC rallies to down league-leading Columbus 3-1|work=[[CP24]]|date=September 27, 2020|access-date=June 22, 2021}}</ref> Laryea was named the MLS Player of the Week as a result of his performance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.torontofc.ca/post/2020/09/28/laryea-named-mls-player-week|title=Laryea named MLS Player of the Week|publisher=[[Toronto FC]]|date=September 28, 2020|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref>

===Nottingham Forest===
On January 8, 2022, [[EFL Championship]] club [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] signed Laryea on a transfer from Toronto FC, signing a three-and-a-half-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/59907565|title=Richie Laryea: Nottingham Forest sign Canada international full-back|work=[[BBC Sport]]|date=January 8, 2022|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> After featuring only sparingly in Forest's matchday squads during his first few months, Laryea made his debut on April 18 against [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]], as a second-half substitute for [[Djed Spence]] in an eventual 4–0 victory.<ref>{{cite tweet|author=[[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest FC]]|user=NFFC|number=1516154239495868416|title=On comes Richie Laryea for his Forest debut, replacing Spence Let's go, Richie #NFFC 3-0 #WBA|date=April 18, 2022|access-date=April 18, 2022}}</ref>

====Loans to Toronto and Vancouver====
In August 2022, he returned on loan to Toronto FC until the end of June 2023.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/soccer/mls/toronto-fc-richie-laryea-mls-august-4-1.6541979|title=Toronto FC moves to bring Richie Laryea back on loan deal after stint in England|date=August 4, 2022|work=[[CBC Sports]]|first=Neil|last=Davidson|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> To complete the transaction, Toronto sent $225,000 in [[Allocation money|General Allocation Money]] to [[FC Dallas]] and $125,000 in General Allocation Money to [[FC Cincinnati]] to acquire the top spot in the MLS Allocation Order.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/soccer/article/toronto-fc-completes-two-side-deals-to-seal-richie-laryeas-return-on-loan/|title=Toronto FC completes two side deals to seal Richie Laryea's return on loan|date=August 5, 2022|work=[[Sportsnet]]|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref>

On August 2, 2023, Laryea was loaned to Canadian MLS side [[Vancouver Whitecaps FC]].<ref>{{Cite web |last= |title=Vancouver Whitecaps acquire Richie Laryea from Nottingham Forest {{!}} MLSSoccer.com |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/vancouver-whitecaps-acquire-richie-laryea-from-nottingham-forest |access-date=August 3, 2023 |website=mlssoccer |language=en}}</ref> In January 2024, it was confirmed that Laryea's move would not be made permanent, and that his time with the club had ended.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theprovince.com/sports/whitecaps-the-richie-laryea-experiment-in-vancouver-is-over|title=Whitecaps: The Richie Laryea experiment in Vancouver is over|website=[[The Province]]|first=J.J.|last=Adams|date=January 5, 2024|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref>

===Return to Toronto===
In February 2024, he returned to [[Toronto FC]] on a permanent transfer, signing a contract through 2026 with an option for 2027.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.torontofc.ca/news/canadian-international-defender-richie-laryea-returns-to-toronto-fc|title=Canadian International Defender Richie Laryea Returns to Toronto FC|date=February 23, 2024|work=[[Toronto FC]]|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref>

==International career==
In May 2016, Laryea was called to [[Canada men's national under-23 soccer team|Canada's U23 national team]] for a pair of [[Exhibition game#Association football|friendlies]] against [[Guyana national football team|Guyana]] and [[Grenada national football team|Grenada]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sirc.ca/news/canada-announces-roster-for-caribbean-tour/|title=Canada announces roster for Caribbean tour|work=SIRC}}</ref> Laryea scored in the opening match against Guyana.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://canadasoccer.com/canada-m23-defeat-guyana-as-part-of-jubilee-celebration-p159523|trans-title=Canada m23 defeat Guyana as part of Jubilee celebration|website=[[Canadian Soccer Association]] |archive-date=August 1, 2017|title=L'équipe U-23 gagne face à Guyana|language=fr|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801040743/https://canadasoccer.com/canada-m23-defeat-guyana-as-part-of-jubilee-celebration-p159523|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref>

Laryea received his first call up to the [[Canada men's national soccer team|senior team]] on August 26, 2019, for two [[2019–20 CONCACAF Nations League|CONCACAF Nations League]] matches against [[Cuba national football team|Cuba]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2019/08/28/canada-names-24-man-roster-concacaf-nations-league-tilts-vs-cuba|date=August 28, 2019|title=Canada names 24-man roster for Concacaf Nations League tilts vs. Cuba|first=Dylan|last=Butler|work=[[Major League Soccer]]|access-date=May 16, 2020}}</ref> He made his debut in the first match on September 7, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://canpl.ca/article/canada-cuba-4-talking-points-for-2nd-nations-league-tilt|title=Canada-Cuba: 4 talking points for 2nd Nations League tilt|date=September 7, 2019|first=Marty|last=Thompson|work=[[Canadian Premier League]]|access-date=May 16, 2020}}</ref>

On March 25, 2021, Laryea scored his first goal for Canada in a 5–1 win over [[Bermuda national football team|Bermuda]] in the team's first [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification – CONCACAF first round|2022 World Cup qualifying]] match.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tsn.ca/cyle-larin-alphonso-davies-combine-to-help-canada-down-bermuda-in-world-cup-qualifier-1.1613675|title=Larin, Davies combine to help Canada down Bermuda in World Cup qualifier|publisher=[[The Sports Network|TSN]]|date=March 25, 2021|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> In June 2021, Laryea was named to [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada]]'s 60-man preliminary squad for the [[2021 CONCACAF Gold Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tsn.ca/canada-names-60-man-preliminary-roster-for-next-month-s-gold-cup-1.1656962|date=June 18, 2021|title=Davies, David highlight Canada's preliminary roster for Gold Cup|work=[[The Sports Network|TSN]]|first=Neil|last=Davidson|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> On July 1, he was named to the final 23-man squad.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.canadasoccer.com/news/canada-soccer-announces-2021-concacaf-gold-cup-roster/|title=Canada Soccer Announces 2021 CONCACAF Gold Cup Roster|work=[[Canadian Soccer Association]]|date=July 1, 2021|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> In November 2022, Laryea was called up to the squad for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://canpl.ca/article/canada-announces-26-man-squad-for-2022-fifa-world-cup-in-qatar|date=November 13, 2022|title=Canada announces 26-man squad for 2022 FIFA World Cup in Qatar|work=[[Canadian Premier League]]|first=Charlie|last=O'Connor-Clarke|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> In June 2023, Laryea was named to Canada's final squad for the [[2023 CONCACAF Nations League Finals]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Łukasz |first=Piszczek |date=2025-08-04 |title=livescore |url=https://livescore.team/ |access-date=2026-05-04 |language=en-CA}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Former CPLers Loturi, Zator called up by Canada for 2023 Concacaf Nations League Finals|date=June 7, 2023|url=https://canpl.ca/article/canada-canmnt-2023-concacaf-nations-league-final-roster|first=Mitchell|last=Tierney|work=[[Canadian Premier League]]|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> On June 19 Laryea was named to the 23-man squad for the [[2023 CONCACAF Gold Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://canpl.ca/article/canmnt-announces-final-23-man-squad-for-concacaf-gold-cup|date=June 19, 2023|work=[[Canadian Premier League]]|title=CanMNT announces final 23-man squad for Concacaf Gold Cup|first=Charlie|last=O'Connor-Clarke|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> In June 2024, Laryea was called-up to the Canadian squad for the [[2024 Copa América]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://canadasoccer.com/news/canmnt-announce-2024-copa-america-roster/|title=CANMNT ANNOUNCE 2024 COPA AMÉRICA ROSTER|date=June 15, 2024|work= [[Canadian Soccer Association]]|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Laryea is of Ghanaian descent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2016/01/10/10-things-about-richie-laryea-his-love-toronto-his-mom-and-yes-drake|title=10 Things About Richie Laryea: His love for Toronto, his mom, and, yes, Drake|first=Arielle|last=Castillo|publisher=[[Major League Soccer]]|date=January 10, 2016|access-date=May 16, 2020}}</ref> His younger brother, Reggie Laryea, plays soccer for semi-professional team [[Vaughan Azzurri]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.league1ontario.com/roster_players/48219384?subseason=678567|publisher=[[League1 Ontario]]|access-date=September 14, 2021|title=Vaughan Azzurri roster|archive-date=September 15, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210915005853/https://www.league1ontario.com/roster_players/48219384?subseason=678567|url-status=dead}}</ref>

